'''USS ''New York'' (BB-34)''' was a [[United States Navy]] [[battleship]], the [[lead ship]] of her [[New York-class battleship|class]]. Named for [[New York State]], she was designed as the first ship to carry the [[14"/45 caliber gun|{{convert|14|in|adj=on|0}}/45-caliber gun]].
Entering service in 1914, she was part of the U.S. Navy force which was sent to reinforce the [[British Grand Fleet]] in the [[North Sea]] near the end of [[World War I]]. During that time, she was involved in at least two incidents with [[German U-boat]]s, and is believed to have been the only US ship to have sunk one in the war, during an accidental collision in October 1918. Following the war, she was sent on a litany of training exercises and cruises in both the Atlantic and the Pacific, and saw several overhauls to increase her armament, aircraft handling and armor.
She entered the [[Neutrality Patrol]] at the beginning of [[World War II]], and served as a convoy escort for ships to [[Iceland]] and [[Great Britain]] in the early phase of the war. She saw her first combat against coastal artillery during [[Operation Torch]] around [[Casablanca]] in [[North Africa]], and later became a training ship. Late in the war, she moved to the [[United States Pacific Fleet|Pacific]], and provided naval gunfire support for the [[Battle of Iwo Jima|invasion of Iwo Jima]] and later the [[Battle of Okinawa|invasion of Okinawa]]. Returning to [[Pearl Harbor]] for repairs until the end of the war, she was classified obsolete and was chosen to take part in the [[Operation Crossroads]] [[nuclear weapon test]]s at [[Bikini Atoll]] in 1946. She survived both explosions and the effects of [[radiation]] on the ship were studied for several years. She was eventually sunk as a target in 1948. She received three [[battle star]]s for her service.
==Design and construction== {{main|New York-class battleship}} ''New York'' was the first of two planned {{sclass-|New York|battleship}}s, though construction on her began after her sister, {{USS|Texas|BB-35|2}}. She was ordered in [[fiscal year]] 1911 as the first class of [[battleship]] in the [[United States Navy]] to carry the 14-inch[[caliber (artillery)|/45-caliber]] gun.{{sfn|Gardiner|Gray|1985|p=114}}{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=27}} [[File:Keel of USS New York (BB-34) (September 12 1911).jpg|left|thumb|Day after keel ceremony, 12 September 1911|alt=A shipyard where construction is beginning on a large ship]]
She had a [[standard displacement]] of {{cvt|27000|LT|lk=on}} and a [[full-load displacement]] of {{cvt|28367|LT}}. She was {{cvt|573|ft|lk=on}} in [[length overall]], {{cvt|565|ft}} [[length at the waterline|at the waterline]], and had a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{cvt|95|ft|6|in}} and a [[draft (nautical)|draft]] of {{cvt|28|ft|6|in}}.{{sfn|Gardiner|Gray|1985|p=115}}
She was powered by 14 [[Babcock & Wilcox]] boilers driving two dual-acting [[vertical triple expansion]] reciprocating steam engines, with {{cvt|28000|shp|lk=on}}, with a maximum speed of {{cvt|21|kn|lk=on}}. She had a [[range (aircraft)|range]] of {{convert|7,060|nmi|lk=on}} at {{cvt|10|kn}}.{{sfn|Gardiner|Gray|1985|p=115}}
Armor on ''New York'' consisted of a [[belt armor|belt]] from {{cvt|10|to|12|in}} thick. Her lower [[casemate]] had between {{cvt|9|and|11|in}} of armor, and her upper casemate had {{cvt|6|in}} of armor. Deck armor was {{cvt|2|in}} thick, and turret armor was {{cvt|14|in}} on the face, {{cvt|4|in}} on the top, 2 inches on the sides, and {{cvt|8|in}} on the rear. Armor on her [[barbettes]] was between 10 and 12 inches. Her conning tower was protected by 12 inches of armor, with 4 inches of armor on its top.{{sfn|Gardiner|Gray|1985|p=115}} [[File:New York 2405649896 ab66402479 o.jpg|left|thumb|250px|Construction in 1912|alt=The hull of a ship near completion]]
Her armament consisted of ten 14-inch/45-caliber guns, arrayed in five double mounts designated 1, 2, 3, 4, and 5. As constructed, these turrets had an elevation of 15 degrees, but this was increased to 30 degrees during an overhaul in 1940–41. The class was the last to feature a turret mounted amidships.{{sfn|Bonner|1996|p=28}}{{sfn|Friedman|2008|p=299}} As built, she also carried twenty-one [[5"/51 caliber gun|{{convert|5|in|adj=on|0}}/51-caliber guns]], primarily for defense against [[destroyer]]s and [[torpedo boat]]s. The 5-inch guns were poor in accuracy in rough seas due to the open casemates mounted in the hull, so the 5-inch armament was reduced to 16 guns in 1918 by removal of the least useful positions near the ends of the ship.{{sfn|Bonner|1996|p=115}} The ship was not designed with [[anti-aircraft]] (AA) defense in mind, but two [[3"/50 caliber gun|{{convert|3|in|adj=on|0}}/50 caliber AA gun]]s were added in 1918.{{sfn|Bonner|1996|p=28}}{{sfn|Friedman|2008|p=304}} She also had four {{convert|21|in|adj=on|0}} [[torpedo tube]]s, 1 each on the port side bow and stern and starboard bow and stern, for the [[Bliss-Leavitt Mark 3 torpedo]]. The torpedo rooms held 12 [[torpedo|torpedoes]] total, plus 12 [[naval mine|naval defense mines]].{{sfn|Friedman|1985|p=436}} Her crew consisted of 1,042 officers and enlisted men.{{sfn|Gardiner|Gray|1985|p=115}}
''New York'' was laid down on 11 September 1911 in [[New York Navy Yard]] in [[Brooklyn]].{{sfn|DANFS|1970|p=552}} The ''New York'' class was constructed under new labor laws that limited the working hours of her construction crews. It was also stipulated that each ship cost less than $6,000,000, excluding cost of armor and armament.{{sfn|Bonner|1996|p=27}} She was launched on 30 October 1912 and [[ship commissioning|commissioned]] on 15 May 1914.{{sfn|Gardiner|Gray|1985|p=115}} The fifth ship to be named for [[New York State]], she was sponsored by Elsie Calder, the daughter of New York politician [[William M. Calder]].{{sfn|DANFS|1970|p=552}}{{sfn|Bonner|1996|p=116}} The fourth {{USS|New York|ACR-2|2}}, an [[armored cruiser]], was renamed ''Rochester'',{{sfn|Davis|2010|p=125}} and was later [[scuttled]] in [[Subic Bay]] in 1941. However, the wreck site for that ship, which has become a popular [[recreational dive site]], is still commonly referred to as USS ''New York''.{{sfn|Davis|2010|p=30}}
==Service history== Under the command of Captain [[Thomas S. Rodgers]],{{sfn|DANFS|1970|p=552}} ''New York'' headed straight for [[Veracruz (city)|Veracruz]] following its commissioning.{{sfn|Gardiner|Gray|1985|p=115}} She was designated [[flagship]] for [[Rear Admiral]] [[Frank Friday Fletcher]] in July 1914, commanding the fleet occupying and blockading Veracruz to prevent arms shipments from arriving there to support the government of [[Victoriano Huerta]]. The [[United States occupation of Veracruz]] ultimately ended and ''New York'' resumed her [[shakedown cruise]] along the [[East Coast of the United States]].{{sfn|Bonner|1996|p=116}} She also undertook several goodwill duties, and in December 1915 she held a high-profile Christmas party and dinner for several hundred orphans from New York City, at the suggestion of her crew. It later became a tradition on the ship to help the underprivileged when possible, earning it the nickname "Christmas Ship." Following this duty, she undertook a number of training exercises off the Atlantic coast.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=31}}
===World War I=== [[File:USS New York-2.jpg|thumb|''New York'' in [[Hampton Roads, Virginia]], December 1916.|alt=A large ship seen from the side]] Following the United States' entry into [[World War I]], ''New York'', under the command of Captain [[Edward L. Beach, Sr.]], became flagship of [[United States Battleship Division Nine (World War I)|Battleship Division 9]] (BatDiv 9), commanded by Rear Admiral [[Hugh Rodman]].{{sfn|Bonner|1996|p=117}} She was sent to reinforce the [[British Grand Fleet]] in the [[North Sea]], arriving at [[Scapa Flow]] on 7 December 1917. The ships of the U.S. fleet were assigned to the [[6th Battle Squadron (United Kingdom)|6th Battle Squadron]] in the Grand Fleet, the American ships joined in [[blockade]] and [[Convoy|escort]].{{sfn|Bonner|1996|p=118}} In December 1917, ''New York'' and the other U.S. battleships took part in several gunnery exercises. ''New York'' scored the highest score of the ships for her main battery, with an accuracy of 93.3 percent.{{sfn|Besch|2001|p=197}} Ultimately the ''New York'' was the best performer in these exercises, the only ship rated as "excellent" while many of her sisters received mediocre performance reviews.{{sfn|Besch|2001|p=198}}
She did not fire any shots during the war, but during at least two occasions, the convoy she was escorting came under attack by German U-boats.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=31}} On the evening of 14 October 1918, as ''New York'' led a group of battleships into the [[Pentland Firth]], she was rocked by a violent underwater collision on her starboard side, followed shortly after by another to the stern that broke off two blades on one of her [[propeller]]s, reducing the ship to one engine and a speed of {{cvt|12|kn|mph km/h}}. It was immediately clear to the men on board that she had struck an underwater object, but the depth of the channel meant it could not have been a [[shipwreck]]. Commanders concluded that ''New York'' must have accidentally collided with a submerged U-boat.{{sfn|Jones|1995|p=66}} They agreed that the submarine had rammed its bow into the ship's side, then been struck moments later by the ship's propeller.{{sfn|Rodman|1927|p=271}} In their opinion, the damage would have been fatal to the German craft.{{sfn|Rodman|1927|p=272}} Postwar examination of German records revealed that the submarine lost may have been {{SMU|UB-113||2}} or {{SMU|UB-123||2}}.{{sfn|Jones|1995|p=67}} This strange—and accidental—encounter marked the only time in all of Battleship Division Nine's service with the Grand Fleet that one of its ships sank a German vessel.{{sfn|Jones|1995|p=67}}
Badly damaged by the loss of a propeller, the ship sailed to [[Rosyth]] under heavy escort for repairs on 15 October. At 01:00 the next morning, a U-boat launched three torpedoes at the damaged vessel, all of which passed ahead of her.{{sfn|Rodman|1927|p=272}} Unlike in previous cases, sufficient evidence existed to suppose that this torpedo attack was not a false alarm—a number of officers and men aboard ''New York'' clearly saw the wakes of the torpedoes in the full [[moonlight]], and a submarine was spotted in the immediate vicinity by a patrol shortly after the attack.{{sfn|Jones|1995|p=67}}{{#tag:ref|Jones notes in his dissertation that German records do not contain any report of a torpedo attack upon a battleship on 16 October 1918. He states that the attack may have come from one of the U-boats that were sunk in the area around that time, however.{{sfn|Jones|1995|p=139}}|group=Note}} Ironically, the battleship's wounded condition is possibly what saved her: although standard procedure was to steam at {{cvt|16|kn|mph km/h}}, ''New York'' could make only {{cvt|12|kn|mph km/h}} on her one operable propeller. Due to this, historian Jerry Jones believes that the U-boat captain misjudged the ship's speed. With no further damage, however, the battleship was able to safely arrive at a [[drydock]] in Rosyth. As she was lifted clear of the water, a large dent commensurate with a submarine bow was found in her hull.{{sfn|Jones|1995|p=67}}
''New York'' was also frequently host to foreign dignitaries, including [[King George V]] and [[Edward VIII]] of the United Kingdom, as well as prince [[Hirohito]] of the [[Empire of Japan]].{{sfn|Bonner|1996|p=118}} The ship was of great interest to other European powers, as it was in many cases a first chance to see an American [[dreadnought]] up close.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=31}} She was on hand for the surrender of the German [[High Seas Fleet]] on 21 November 1918 in the [[Firth of Forth]], several days after the signing of the [[Armistice with Germany|Armistice]], after which she returned to the United States briefly.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=32}} She then served as an escort for {{ship|SS|George Washington||2}}, carrying President [[Woodrow Wilson]], on his trip from the United States to [[Brest, France]] ''en route'' to the [[Paris Peace Conference, 1919|Versailles Peace Conference]].{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=32}}
===Interwar period=== Arriving back in the United States in 1919, she began to undertake training and patrol duties, including at one point to the [[Caribbean]] with a number of other U.S. ships.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=32}} During this year, she also saw a refit in [[Norfolk Navy Yard]] where five 5-inch guns were removed and three additional 3-inch/50 caliber AA guns were added, bringing the total to five.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=33}} The secondary battery was reduced to sixteen 5-inch/51 caliber guns.{{sfn|Breyer|1973|p=205}} In late 1919, she sailed to the [[Pacific Ocean]] and joined the newly formed [[United States Pacific Fleet]].{{sfn|Bonner|1996|p=118}} She continued to conduct training and patrol duties in the Pacific until the mid-1930s when she was transferred again to the [[United States Atlantic Fleet|Atlantic]], and began operating out of the [[North Atlantic]], with the exception of several occasional trips to the [[West Coast of the United States]].{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=32}}
[[File:USS New York-4.jpg|thumb|left|250px|''New York'' on maneuvers with {{USS|Oklahoma|BB-37|2}} and {{USS|Nevada|BB-36|2}}, 1932|alt=Three large warships steaming in single file through the water]] In 1926 ''New York'' was considered obsolete compared with other battleships in service, so she steamed to Norfolk Navy Yard for a complete refit. While several other battleships in service, including {{USS|Utah|BB-31|2}} and {{USS|Florida|BB-30|2}} were converted to training ships or scrapped, ''New York'' and ''Texas'' were chosen to be overhauled to increase their speed, armor, armament, and propulsion systems as allowed by the [[Washington Naval Treaty]] of 1922.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=32}} An additional {{cvt|3000|LT|}} were added to her for defense against aerial targets and submarines. The number of 3-inch AA guns was increased to 8, and six of the 5-inch guns were relocated to new casemates on the main deck. The torpedo tubes were removed at this time. Her 14 Babcock & Wilcox [[coal-fired]] [[boilers]] were replaced with six Bureau Express oil-fired boilers and the twin funnels were trunked into one, aft of the forward superstructure. Tripods were fitted in place of lattice masts, and atop the forward tripod a control tower was installed. A tower was built amidships that contained additional fire control to backup the system on the foremast. A new [[aircraft catapult]] was installed atop turret Number 3 and cranes were installed on either side of the funnel for boat and aircraft handling. Additional deck protection was added, and her beam was widened to {{cvt|106|ft}}. She was fitted with [[anti-torpedo bulge]]s. However, these bulges made maneuvering harder at low speeds, she rolled badly, and her gunfire accuracy was reduced in rough seas.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=33}} On 4 September 1928, she left for short-range battle drills with {{USS|Arizona|BB-39|2}}, and from 7 to 10 November the ships traveled to [[San Francisco]] together with {{USS|Pennsylvania|BB-38|2}}.{{sfn|Stillwell|1991|p=313}} On 3 April 1929 she undertook anti-aircraft practice with ''Arizona'', and then the two ships and ''Pennsylvania'' steamed for [[Cuba]], where they stayed until steaming for [[Hampton Roads]] on 1 May.{{sfn|Stillwell|1991|p=314}}
She remained with the Pacific Fleet training as part of the series of [[Fleet Problem]]s until 1937. That year she was selected to carry Admiral [[Hugh Rodman]], the President's personal representative for the [[coronation of King George VI and Queen Elizabeth]], and ''New York'' took part in the [[Fleet Review, Royal Navy|Grand Naval Review]] of 20 May 1937 as sole U.S. Navy representative.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=34}} In 1937, eight [[1.1"/75 caliber gun|{{convert|1.1|in|adj=on|0}}/75 caliber]] AA guns in two quadruple mounts were added to improve the light AA armament. ''New York'' was fitted with [[XAF radar]] in February 1938, including the first United States [[duplexer]] so a single antenna could both send and receive.{{sfn|Macintyre|1967|p=73}} This made her the second ship to be outfitted with radar after the destroyer {{USS|Leary|DD-158|2}}. The tests conducted on ''New York'' led to similar radars being installed on the {{sclass-|Brooklyn|cruiser|0}} and {{sclass-|St. Louis|cruiser (1938)|0}} [[cruisers]] as well as newer battleship {{USS|West Virginia|BB-48|2}}. For several years, she served primarily as a training ship for midshipmen and newly enlisted sailors.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=34}}
In September 1939, ''New York'' joined the [[Neutrality Patrol]], safeguarding sea lanes in the North Atlantic, and served with the Atlantic Squadron, later redesignated the United States Atlantic Fleet, for the next 27 months.{{sfn|Bonner|1996|p=119}} In July 1941, she protected a convoy of U.S. troops moving to [[Invasion of Iceland#United States occupation force|garrison Iceland]].{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=34}} She saw another modernization in 1940–41 where her main battery elevation was increased from 15 to 30 degrees.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=33}} She was in the midst of this refit on 7 December 1941, when the [[Japan|Imperial Japanese]] [[Imperial Japanese Navy|Navy]] [[attack on Pearl Harbor|attacked Pearl Harbor]], sinking many of the battleships in the U.S. Pacific Fleet and bringing the United States into [[World War II]].{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=35}}
===World War II=== With the outbreak of war, ''New York''{{'}}s overhaul was sped up and completed four weeks after the attack on Pearl Harbor. She returned to duty escorting cargo and troop ships to Iceland and [[Scotland]]. She continued on patrol duty for the next year.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=35}} In her first series of escorts, she left Norfolk 15 February, arrived in New York 16 February, Nova Scotia 21 February, and Iceland 2 March, returning to Norfolk on 27 March. She left there on her second patrol 24 April and arrived at New York the next day, Nova Scotia 2 May, [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland]] 5 May, and Iceland 10 May, returning to New York on 20 May. The next day she left for a third escort, arriving again at Nova Scotia on 2 June and Scotland on 10 June, returning to Norfolk on 30 June.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=42}}{{sfn|Bonner|1996|p=120}} Following these three escort missions, she put in for overhaul in Norfolk. The secondary battery was reduced to six 5-inch (127&nbsp;mm) guns and the anti-aircraft armament was increased to ten 3-inch/50 caliber guns, 24 [[Bofors 40 mm|{{convert|40|mm|abbr=on}} Bofors guns]] in quadruple mounts, and 42 [[Oerlikon 20 mm cannon|{{convert|20|mm|abbr=on}} Oerlikon cannons]].{{sfn|Breyer|1973|p=205}} She departed Norfolk on 12 August and arrived the next day at New York. From there, she escorted a convoy to [[Nova Scotia]] where she remained until 22 August, then departed for Scotland where she was from 31 August to 5 September. She returned to Norfolk on 15 September.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=43}}
[[File:USS New York-5.jpg|thumb|left|''New York'' off North Africa just after the battle at Casablanca|alt=A large warship painted in camouflage pattern]] ''New York'' saw her first major action during [[Operation Torch]], the [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] invasion of [[North Africa]] in November 1942. She left Norfolk on 23 October in order to join the Allied fleet.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=43}} Attached to the Southern Attack Group, on 8 November, ''New York'' and the cruiser {{USS|Philadelphia|CL-41|2}}, screened by six destroyers, attacked Safi harbor in Morocco, supporting landings by the [[9th Infantry Division (United States)|U.S. 9th Infantry Division's 47th Infantry Regiment]], and defended the transports {{USS|Cole|DD-155|2}} and {{USS|Bernadou|DD-153|2}} which came under attack by {{convert|130|mm|adj=on|sp=us}} [[shore batteries]] at Point De La Tour.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=35}} ''New York'' fired several salvoes with her {{convert|14|in|adj=on}} guns, with one of them striking the base of the battery and ricocheting into a bunker, destroying the range finder and killing the battery commander and neutralizing the battery.{{sfn|Bonner|1996|p=120}} Other shore batteries were destroyed by ''Philadelphia''{{'}}s guns and aircraft from [[escort carrier]] {{USS|Santee|CVE-29|2}}. ''New York'' remained on station until the port was secure, then steamed north to support the Center Group off [[Fedhala]] and [[Casablanca]], specifically to deal with the threat of the [[Vichy France|Vichy French]] battleship [[French battleship Jean Bart (1940)|''Jean Bart'']], but by the time she arrived, that battleship had been disabled by {{USS|Massachusetts|BB-59|2}} and other Vichy French ships had been driven off by {{USS|Brooklyn|CL-40|2}} and {{USS|Augusta|CA-31|2}}. ''New York'' remained on off the coast of North Africa until the beaches were secure, then retired on 14 November.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=36}} She had expended a total of sixty {{convert|14|in|adj=on}} rounds.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=40}} She returned to Norfolk on 23 November.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=43}}{{sfn|Bonner|1996|p=120}}
''New York'' next returned to convoy patrol.{{sfn|Bonner|1996|p=121}} She escorted two convoys to Casablanca from the United States during late 1942, leaving Norfolk on 24 November and in New York from 25 November to 12 December, Casablanca from 24 to 29 December, and back in Norfolk on 12 January 1943. She left Norfolk on the second escort on 26 February, in New York from 27 February to 5 March, in Casablanca from 18 to 25 March, and back to New York from 5 April to 1 May.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=43}} In 1943 she was selected for a refit to become a main battery and escort training center.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=36}} She arrived in [[Portland, Maine]] on 2 May, where she remained until 27 July.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=43}} During her fourth and final refit in early 1943 her anti-aircraft battery was increased to ten 3-inch/50 caliber guns, forty 40mm and thirty-six 20mm guns. Improved fire control was added as well, and this ultimately increased her displacement to {{cvt|29340|LT|}} standard and {{cvt|34000|LT}} full-load.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=33}} She returned to Norfolk on 2 August 1943.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=43}} She was used to train crews from the US Navy, [[US Coast Guard]], and Allied navies on the 14-inch/45 caliber gun, the 3-inch/50 caliber gun, and the 20mm and 40mm guns, primarily because many newer ships used these weapons. Between July 1943 and June 1944 about 11,000 enlisted men and 750 officers trained on her in this capacity.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=36}} However, the duty lowered morale among the crew and a large number of requests for transfer were put in.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=43}} Following this duty, she was sent to the [[US Naval Academy]] and undertook three consecutive midshipmen cruises ferrying a total of 1,800 cadets from Annapolis to [[Trinidad]]{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=37}} between June and August 1944.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=44}}
====Pacific theater==== [[File:USS New York-11.jpg|thumb|''New York'' firing her 14-inch main guns on [[Iwo Jima]] on 16 February 1945|alt=Seen from the side of a ship as large guns fire toward targets out of sight]] Selected to return to action in the [[Pacific Theater of World War II|Pacific Theater]]{{sfn|Bonner|1996|p=122}} in late 1944, she transited the [[Panama Canal]] on 27 November, and arrived in [[Long Beach, California]] on 9 December, breaking down at least once along the way and losing an observation plane in bad weather.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=44}} She conducted refresher training off [[Southern California]] in December 1944 and January 1945. ''New York'' departed 12 January and rendezvoused with {{USS|Idaho|BB-42|2}}, {{USS|Tennessee|BB-43|2}}, {{USS|Nevada|BB-36|2}}, ''Texas'', and {{USS|Arkansas|BB-33|2}}, forming a support force for the [[Battle of Iwo Jima|invasion of Iwo Jima]]. ''New York'' lost a blade off her port screw just before the invasion began{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=37}} and briefly put in for temporary repairs at [[Eniwetok]] from 5 to 7 February. She returned to the group, which was near [[Saipan]], on 11 February. Together, they arrived at Iwo Jima on 16 February and began the pre-invasion bombardment.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=44}} During the three days of shore bombardment that followed, ''New York'' expended 6,417 rounds, including 1,037 14-inch rounds. One of her salvoes struck the primary ammunition dump on the island, causing "the most spectacular secondary explosion in the campaign."{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=37}} She retired from the area on 19 February and arrived at [[Ulithi]] on 21 February.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=44}}
[[File:USS New York-7.jpg|thumb|left|upright|''New York'' arrives in New York Harbor for 1945 [[Navy Day]] celebrations]] After a permanent repair to her port propeller at [[Manus Island|Manus]] from 28 February to 19 March, she rejoined [[Task Force 54]] at Ulithi on 22 March{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=45}} in preparation for the [[Battle of Okinawa|invasion of Okinawa]]. Joined by {{USS|Maryland|BB-46|2}}, {{USS|Colorado|BB-45|2}}, and ''West Virginia'', the fleet of battleships began its bombardment of [[Okinawa]] on 27 March.{{sfn|Bonner|1996|p=122}} Providing shore bombardment, and later [[naval artillery support]] for ground forces, ''New York'' was on station for 76 consecutive days, during which she expended 4,159 rounds of 14-inch ammunition and 7,001 rounds of 5-inch ammunition.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=37}}{{sfn|Breyer|1973|p=205}} She was subjected to a ''[[kamikaze]]'' attack on 14 April which destroyed one spotting plane on its catapult, but the Japanese aircraft crashed {{cvt|50|yd}} from the ship and ''New York'' received only superficial damage, suffering two men injured.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=40}} She was detached on 11 June, her gun barrels having been worn out by fire, and proceeded to Pearl Harbor to have her guns relined in preparation for [[Operation Downfall|the invasion of mainland Japan]].{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=38}} She stopped by [[Leyte]] on 14 June and arrived at Pearl Harbor on 1 July.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=45}} She was in the harbor on 15 August, the end of the war.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=38}}
During World War II, ''New York'' spent 1,088 days with the Atlantic Fleet from December 1941 to November 1944, and 276 days with the Pacific Fleet.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=40}} She expended a total of 53,094 rounds of all types totaling {{cvt|3548.9|ST}}, traveled {{cvt|123867|mi}}, spent 414 days underway, and consumed {{cvt|22367996|gal}} of fuel oil.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=41}}
===Post-war=== [[File:Crossroads Baker Hosedown.jpg|thumb|The Baker shot of Operation Crossroads, Bikini Atoll, 25 July 1946. A navy fireboat washes down ''New York'' with seawater, in an attempt to reduce radioactive contamination after the base surge passed over it.|alt=A large, damaged, stripped warship being hosed down by a smaller boat]]
Following the end of the war, ''New York'' entered the [[Operation Magic Carpet]] fleet, leaving Pearl Harbor on 2 September and arriving at [[San Pedro Bay (California)|San Pedro]] on 9 September with a load of veterans embarked. She then proceeded to New York City to take part in [[Navy Day]] celebrations.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=45}}
Selected as a test ship for [[Operation Crossroads]], she was used in bomb tests at [[Bikini Atoll]] in July 1946 with about 70 other ships, surviving both the Able and Baker nuclear tests. Following these tests, she was towed to Pearl Harbor to study the effects of the bomb blasts on her. On 6 July 1948, she was towed out to sea and used as target practice, and was sunk by several naval aircraft and ships.{{sfn|Banks|2002|p=38}} She had received three [[Battle star#Navy warships|battle stars]] for her wartime service.{{sfn|DANFS|1970|p=552}}
===In fiction=== In the [[Isaac Bell]] Adventure, ''[[The Spy (Cussler novel)|The Spy]]'' by [[Clive Cussler]] & [[Justin Scott (writer)|Justin Scott]], the year is 1908 and there is a spy sabotaging American battleship development. ''New York'', known as "Hull 44," is a secret advanced design [[dreadnought]] that is being built during the novel.
